sentences: Cast the First Stone was released in 1985 and became a minor success with the single "Running Back"[1] peaking at #79 on the Billboard Hot 100.
The 1987 Tom Allom produced follow-up album, Thinking Out Loud, which spawned the single/video "Can't Take It No More"[2], was not a success and the band split up.

Yul Vazquez, along with drummer Peter Clemente, would join former Plasmatics man Jean Beauvoir on his Drums Along the Mohawk tour before both joined Diving For Pearls whose eponymous debut album was released via Epic Records in 1989.
Vazquez segued into an acting career starting in 1992 with the movie The Mambo Kings and had a memorable recurring role on Seinfeld between 1995 and '98 as Bob, The Intimidating Gay Guy.
Bassist Klyph Black was also a member of Detroit, MI power trio Vendetta, featuring guitarist/vocalist Nikki Buzz, whose Max Norman produced album was issued on Epic Records in 1982.
Black and Clemente both appear on Monroe's 1987 debut solo album, Nights Are So Long.
Michael and Steve Kehr were members of pop rock band Sterling who released the album City Kids, produced by David Kershenbaum, on A&M Records in 1980.
